{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566365"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:40:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:40:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18798"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18798"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.06,0.1,0.71,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18798"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38455"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe intern covering the General Medicine Ward is called by nursing staff at 2AM to urgently review a 72-year-old woman for dyspnoea. The patient has been admitted with community-acquired pneumonia and has just been transferred to the ward from the Emergency Department. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her home medications include amlodipine and paracetamol which she has not taken today. She received her first doses of intravenous ceftriaxone and azithromycin four hours ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears visibly breathless and is using accessory muscles of respiration. Her pulse rate is 114/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She is able to speak in short phrases only. Chest auscultation reveals widespread crackles throughout both lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Request urgent chest X-ray","Escalate antibiotics to piperacillin-tazobactam","Commence intravenous furosemide","Commence nasal prong oxygen","Administer glyceryl trinitrate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of respiratory deterioration in the context of known pneumonia. The vital signs show tachypnoea, hypoxia, and early signs of cardiovascular compromise with tachycardia and relative hypotension. The immediate priority is to address the patient\u0027s oxygenation using the airway, breathing, circulation approach to emergency management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence nasal prong oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as it will immediately address the patient\u0027s hypoxia (SpO2 92% on room air). This basic intervention can be initiated quickly while simultaneously assessing the patient and considering other interventions. Improving her oxygen saturations will also help relieve some of her tachypnoea and dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest urgent chest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate later but should not delay immediate resuscitation measures. Since she has just been admitted from the Emergency Department, she has likely already had recent chest imaging. Repeat imaging may help identify complications such as pleural effusions if her clinical condition fails to improve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscalate antibiotics to piperacillin-tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if treatment failure is suspected, but this is not the immediate priority in an acutely hypoxic patient. The current antibiotics have only been running for four hours and need more time to take effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence intravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered if there was evidence of fluid overload contributing to her respiratory distress. However, the widespread crackles are more likely related to her pneumonia rather than cardiac failure, and diuresis is not the immediate priority when hypoxia needs urgent correction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister glyceryl trinitrate\u003C/strong\u003E is a vasodilator that might be considered in acute heart failure with pulmonary oedema. However, this patient\u0027s presentation is more consistent with pneumonia-related respiratory compromise, and her blood pressure is already relatively low at 95/60 mmHg, making vasodilation potentially harmful.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rapid assessment of airway, breathing, and circulation is essential in any emergency call.","Oxygen therapy should be commenced immediately in hypoxic patients before other investigations or treatments.","Clear communication with nursing staff about ongoing monitoring and escalation parameters is crucial."],"references":["Hashmi MF, Modi P, Basit H, et al. Dyspnea. [Updated 2023 Feb 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499965/","SA Health. Adult Observation and Response Chart (MR59A) \u2013 Example. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/ff3a769a-e8f0-45db-970e-12281b2891b2/MR59A%2B-%2BAdult%2BObservation%2BChart%2B-%2BEXAMPLE+%281%29.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-ff3a769a-e8f0-45db-970e-12281b2891b2-p549CV9"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88115"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18798"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88115"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T12:04:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T12:47:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11531"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,